    <item>
      <title>Keihard tenderen voor een nieuwe auto met Carwoo!</title>
      <description>Het bestaat al een aantal maanden maar begint nu toch wel serieuze vormen aan te nemen. Online tenderen voor een nieuwe auto. En het online aanschaffen van een nieuwe auto. Ook al zijn autodealers van mening dat het nog vrij marginaal is; zeker een ontwikkeling om in de gaten te houden! &lt;a target="_blank" href="http://carwoo.com/"&gt;Carwoo!&lt;/a&gt; is de afgelopen maanden enorm in populairiteit gestegen. Via &lt;a target="_blank" href="http://carwoo.com/"&gt;Carwoo!&lt;/a&gt; kun je autodealers tegen elkaar op laten bieden op een door jou gekozen nieuwe auto. De offertes zijn voor alle dealers zichtbaar. &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;De claim van &lt;a target="_blank" href="http://www.carwoo.com"&gt;Carwoo!&lt;/a&gt; richting de autokoper is duidelijk; &lt;em&gt;Simply the best way to buy your new car.&lt;br /&gt;Save time, money, and your sanity!&lt;/em&gt; En juist dat laatste woordje is een flinke steek richting de autobranche. Naar eigen zeggen heeft Carwoo! &amp;#39;over $12,525,418 in savings offered to thousands of satisfied CarWoo! buyers&amp;#39;. Naast Carwoo! bieden websites als &lt;a target="_blank" href="http://www.truecar.com"&gt;Truecar.com&lt;/a&gt; inzicht in verkoopprijzen, marges en meer op basis van automerken en regio. Ultieme transparantie in deze markt dus.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Bekijk deze mooie video maar eens, als je in Amerika woont koop je voortaan je auto online!&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;iframe frameborder="0" height="401" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/F_4B_dDgpHE?hd=0&amp;amp;autoplay=1&amp;amp;rel=0" title="YouTube video player" type="text/html" width="660"&gt;&lt;/iframe&gt; &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;In Nederland kun je overigens via &lt;a target="_blank" href="http://www.autodealershopper.nl/"&gt;Autodealershopper.nl&lt;/a&gt; ook meerdere offertes tegelijk opvragen. En via &lt;a target="_blank" href="http://www.nieuweautokopen.nl"&gt;Nieuweautokopen.nl&lt;/a&gt; kun je direct online een nieuwe auto kopen. Inclusief inruil van je huidige auto. Dealers zullen niet blij zijn met deze ontwikkeling, maar in een &lt;a target="_blank" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Commodity"&gt;commodity-markt&lt;/a&gt; is dit niet tegen te houden. &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Dat er gretig gebruikt gemaakt wordt betekent voor de dealers vooral dat ze snel op zoek moeten naar nieuwe businessmodellen waarin ze (wel) waarde toevoegen. Of snoeihard gaan voor lage prijzen en een hoog volume. Maar die stap zal vanuit &lt;a target="_blank" href="http://www.automotive-online.nl/home/7848-bovag_groei_nieuwverkoop_universelen_5procent_per_jaar_%28video%29.html"&gt;de universelen&lt;/a&gt; komen, want dealers zitten voor verkoop natuurlijk vast aan hun verzorgingsgebied. Nog zo&amp;#39;n ouderwetse gedachte in een tijdperk waarin de wereld het speelveld is...&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;</description>
      <link>http://www.mindz.com/plazas/Happydriver_com_Nederland/blog/14432</link>
      <author>Jeroen van der Schenk</author>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">http://www.mindz.com/plazas/Happydriver_com_Nederland/blog/14432</guid>
      <pubDate>Tue, 19 Oct 2010 06:04:00 GMT</pubDate>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Unfair? You Bet it is…</title>
      <description>&amp;quot;Buyers are liars&amp;quot; ... I don&amp;rsquo;t think I was in the car business one hour before I heard that catchy little phrase. Sure enough, over the course of my retail career, I suspect I was lied to over and over again by the best of them.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;I&amp;rsquo;m not going to pontificate about what buyers lie about and why &amp;ndash; many of us could easily write a book on that subject. Instead I&amp;rsquo;m going to bring up what I think is an important point &amp;ndash; buyers can say pretty much whatever they want without fear of recourse, dealers cannot. Yep, that&amp;rsquo;s right. Buyers can outright lie through their teeth, but dealers are not allowed to stretch the truth even a little.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Doesn&amp;rsquo;t seem fair, does it? Well it&amp;rsquo;s not. All may be fair in love and war, but it sure isn&amp;rsquo;t fair on a car lot. For the most part, when buyers lie to a dealer, they get to go on their merry old way. But if a dealership is accused of being dishonest with a customer, either by commission or omission, they may end up in a courtroom or worse.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;When you look at actual enforcement actions and court cases against dealerships, there is typically one common element &amp;ndash; the perception that the dealer was less than completely honest with a consumer. The laws allow for a very broad interpretation of what is considered to be unfair or deceptive. Here are some common examples of accusations by plaintiff&amp;rsquo;s attorneys and regulators:&lt;br /&gt;&lt;ul&gt;&lt;li&gt;Making false statements or failing to disclose a material facts to a consumer&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;Oral promises made to the consumer that the dealer fails to deliver upon&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;Misleading statements about APR, such as &amp;ldquo;You won&amp;rsquo;t be able to get a better interest rate than this&amp;rdquo;, when the buy rate is being marked up&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;Communicating information in a manner that may be misleading, either by commission or omission&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;Adding the cost of an F&amp;amp;I product to a consumer&amp;rsquo;s purchase agreement or lease without first obtaining the consumer&amp;rsquo;s express consent to purchase the product&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;Informing or suggesting to a consumer that the price of any F&amp;amp;I product is included in the price of the motor vehicle&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;Informing or suggesting to a consumer that the sale or lease of a vehicle subject to credit approval is a final or completed transaction&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;Altering documents without the knowledge and permission of all parties&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;Obtaining a credit bureau without proper authorization&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;Failing to sell a vehicle at or below an advertised price, whether or not the consumer knows about the advertisement&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;Advertising vehicles with intent not to sell them as advertised&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;Misrepresenting discounts in advertising and not disclosing important limitations&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;Advertising claims such as &amp;quot;everyone financed,&amp;quot; &amp;quot;no credit rejected,&amp;quot; or similar claims when the dealer is unwilling to extend credit to any person under any and all circumstances&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;Engaging in false or misleading advertising, either orally or by way of media&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;Advertising &amp;ldquo;no money down&amp;rdquo; or &amp;ldquo;zero drive off&amp;rdquo; when there is actually some money needed to achieve the advertised payment amount (such as tax, license, acquisition fee, etc.)&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;Representing to a consumer that a vehicle is available for sale when it is not&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;Informing or suggesting to a consumer that an F&amp;amp;I product is a required purchase&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;Informing or suggesting to a consumer that purchase of an F&amp;amp;I product will increase the likelihood that the consumer will be approved for financing or that financing will be approved on more favorable terms to the consumer&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;Increasing the selling price of a vehicle to cover a bank acquisition fee&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;Intentionally overstating a vehicle&amp;rsquo;s value by supplying an incorrect book-sheet or due bill to a financial institution&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;Over-allowing on a trade-in, thereby increasing the sale price of the purchased vehicle or failing to properly disclose negative equity&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;Misrepresenting the amount of rebates available to a customer&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;Engaging in payment packing, i.e. inflating payments, inflating down payments, extending the contract term or in any way disguising the actual charges for goods or services.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;Knowingly delivering a vehicle where the lender or lessor will not approve the consumer for financing according to the terms set forth in the installment sales or lease contract, with the intention of re-writing the contract at a later date&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;Failing to properly disclose deferred down payments&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;Knowingly misrepresenting a vehicle&amp;rsquo;s prior history or condition, either by commission or omission&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;Forging documents&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;Knowingly misrepresenting a vehicle, products or the terms being offered&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;Falsifying, or allowing to be falsified, any information on a credit application&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;Knowingly allowing a consumer to participate in a &amp;ldquo;straw purchase&amp;rdquo;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;Misrepresenting the scope or extent of coverage under a service contract or warranty&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;It&amp;rsquo;s more important than ever to be very careful when dealing with customers. Plaintiff&amp;rsquo;s attorneys are constantly on the prowl for cases and regulators recognize the political capital in going after dealers. There&amp;rsquo;s just no upside to being accused of lying. The good news is that you can feel free to lie to car salespeople in your spare time...</description>
      <link>http://www.mindz.com/plazas/Happydriver_com_Nederland/blog/13798</link>
      <author>Jim Radogna</author>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">http://www.mindz.com/plazas/Happydriver_com_Nederland/blog/13798</guid>
      <pubDate>Wed, 08 Sep 2010 09:59:00 GMT</pubDate>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Unhappy Car Buyer Gets 110,000 Views on YouTube</title>
      <description>I was browsing through the website of a prominent dealer-chasing law firm this morning (I know, I have weird hobbies), and came across a posting about a dealer with a link to a YouTube video. This &lt;a target="_blank" href="http://www.mossyusedcars.com/en/index"&gt;dealership&lt;/a&gt; is part of a good-sized group that is very well-regarded in the area. As I am personally acquainted with this dealer group, I can attest to their integrity and dedication to customer satisfaction. So, when I clicked on the YouTube link, I expected to see another unconvincing customer with a bad case of buyer&amp;rsquo;s remorse. Well, I wasn&amp;rsquo;t disappointed &amp;ndash; the customer bought a cheap older car and expected it to run like a brand-new Mercedes.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Not surprisingly, &lt;a target="_blank" href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9sCUmXfy03c"&gt;the video&lt;/a&gt; attempted to make the dealership look terrible and completely at fault. But here&amp;rsquo;s the thing - this video wasn&amp;rsquo;t an amateurish clip of a customer ranting and raving, it was obviously professionally done. So well done in fact that I suspect most consumers viewing the video would find it believable.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Then I noticed the view count on &lt;a target="_blank" href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9sCUmXfy03c"&gt;the video&lt;/a&gt;. Just short of 110,000 views so far, most of which are from the last month or so. Needless to say, I was astounded! One car deal, one customer, one dealership, over 100 thousand views? No way, this has to be a mistake.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;object height="405" width="500"&gt;&lt;param name="wmode" value="transparent" /&gt;&lt;param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/9sCUmXfy03c?fs=1&amp;amp;hl=nl_NL&amp;amp;rel=0&amp;amp;border=1" /&gt;&lt;param name="allowFullScreen" value="true" /&gt;&lt;param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always" /&gt;&lt;embed wmode="transparent" allowfullscreen="true" allowscriptaccess="always" height="405" src="http://www.youtube.com/v/9sCUmXfy03c?fs=1&amp;amp;hl=nl_NL&amp;amp;rel=0&amp;amp;border=1" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" width="500"&gt;&lt;/embed&gt;&lt;/object&gt; &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Sadly, it&amp;rsquo;s no mistake. Here&amp;rsquo;s how it happened:&lt;br /&gt;The video was produced by a &lt;a target="_blank" href="http://www.carconsumers.org/"&gt;consumer group&lt;/a&gt; (C.A.R.S. - Consumers for Auto Reliability and Safety) who naturally had an agenda of their own. While the customer&amp;rsquo;s initial complaint was that the car had problems and he wanted his money back, a good portion of the video dealt with how the customer was saddled with an unfair arbitration agreement by the dealer. Now, according to the clip, the poor customer can&amp;rsquo;t get his day in court, has had to wait years for his arbitration hearing, has little or no chance of winning in arbitration because it&amp;rsquo;s skewed towards the dealer, and all kinds of other nonsense.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The arbitration issue is what caused this video to go viral. Consumer groups and plaintiff&amp;rsquo;s attorneys have been lobbying against arbitration agreements for years. This is just another sneaky way to promote their agenda. There are now links to this video on consumer sites, legal blogs, you name it. The worst part is that the video shows up on page one when you Google the dealership or search on YouTube. It&amp;rsquo;s just a darn shame.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;hr align="right" width="100%" /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;img align="left" src="/images/jimradogna/jim_radogna20100908034009.jpg" style="padding-right: 5px; padding-bottom: 5px; width: 57px; height: 57px;" /&gt;Created by Jim Radogna&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;President at Dealer Compliance Consultants, Inc.&lt;br /&gt;Source: &lt;a target="_blank" href="http://dealercomplianceconsultants.blogspot.com/2010/08/unhappy-car-buyer-gets-110000-views-on.html"&gt;Auto Dealer Compliance &amp;amp; Reputation Management&lt;/a&gt;</description>
      <link>http://www.mindz.com/plazas/Happydriver_com_Nederland/blog/13792</link>
      <author>Jim Radogna</author>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">http://www.mindz.com/plazas/Happydriver_com_Nederland/blog/13792</guid>
